Incidence

Background

There are multiple different types of cancer. We would like to find out which types have been recorded in Scotland and how these have changed over time.

Different cancers are categorised (coded) according to World Health Organisation (WHO) International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (ICD). In Scotland, currently the ‘ICD-10’ code is used when a patient is diagnosed to record which type of cancer they have. Example of an ICD-10 code: C50 = ‘Breast’ cancer.

Terminology

Technical terms used relating to this dataset.

Term Description
incidence The total number of new cases (registrations) of the cancer diagnosed in Scotland for the given period.
cancer site The place where a cancer starts in the body. This is represented as a code and also a human readable name.

The Scottish Cancer Registry and Intelligence Service (SCRIS) collects detailed information on every cancer in Scotland. However, this raw information is not public and can only be directly accessed by people in the NHS and approved individuals.

Public Health Scotland (PHS) makes available extracts from the SCRIS as open data. For this analysis the Annual Cancer Incidence data will be used. Specifically Incidence at Scotland Level. Annual number and rate of new cancer registrations in Scotland by sex and age.

Cancer incidence in Scotland To December 2021)

The following dataset gives us an annual number and rate of new cancer registrations in Scotland by sex and age. Reports include data from 1997 to 2021.

Source: Incidence at Scotland Level. PHS Last update: 29 March 2023.

This analysis utilises PHS data. Their sex data uses ‘Females’ plural but “Male” singular, this has been left to match the original.

Important! When is a medical cancer a ‘cancer’ in official reports?

“‘All cancers’ by convention excludes non-melanoma skin cancers.” - PHS.

Non-melanoma skin cancers are in the original open data supplied. To keep consistent with the official reporting standard ‘Non-melanoma skin cancers’ have been excluded from this analysis. -
Cancer incidence in Scotland To December 2021

Analysis

This dataset covers years 1997-2021.

Time: Cancer Incidences by Year and Sex

The higher the incidences, the more people have been formally diagnosed as having a new case of cancer. Shows incidences in general, started increasing in number in 1998 to 2018. Then dropped from 2019 to 2020 (start of COVID). In most recent year of results available 2021 numbers rose sharply to the highest level ever.

Summary: Incidences by Sex

Summary statistics Incidences by Sex
Data between: 1997 and 2021
Result Total Mean Median
All 749,411 29,976 30,634
Females 383,143 15,326 15,615
Male 366,268 14,651 14,766
Data Source: Public Health Scotland

On average in Scotland there are almost 30,000 new incidences of cancer each year. Females have a higher average(mean) and median number of incidences per year than males but bear in mind there is a slightly higher number of females in the population of Scotland. These figures are relatively close in spite of sexes having some completely different types of cancer risk due to different organs.

The 2021 estimates for Scotland’s population produced by National Records of Scotland (NRS) show that Scotland’s overall population stands at 5.48 million: 2.67 million males and 2.8 million females.
Population: estimates, Scotland, Scottish Public Health Observatory

Displays the summary statistics for yearly incidences for both sexes. Even taking COVID-19 in to account there are no outliers - no years stand out as being significantly different from the others. The median for females is higher and males and the distribution is more negatively skewed.

Years with highest/lowest cancer incidences
Data between: 1997 and 2021
Result Incidences Year
Highest 35,379 2021
Lowest 12,432 1999
Data Source: Public Health Scotland

Cancer incidences had been steadily increasing since the late 1990s before starting to drop in 2019, note this was the year before COVID-19 started. Unfortunately the most recent year of data the cases are at their highest number ever. This has to be caveated with our growing and ageing population. So the drop on the year of COVID-19 itself might have been part of an already decreasing trend. There was widespread disruption to health services and daily life. All manner of primary care (e.g. GP practices) and diagnostic services were interrupted completely or on heavily reduced capacity which may give some administrative reasons for a drop in formal diagnoses. The steep rise 2020-2021 may have a backlog of previously undiagnosed cases as part of that increase.

GPs commented at the time that a lot of patients weren’t coming to them. they are often the first point of contact for those with symptoms/concerns eventually leading to a formal cancer diagnosis. “GPs are worried about “missing patients” and the backlog which has built up in chronic disease management, screening, immunisation and cancer referrals.” DEEP END REPORT 36 General Practice in the time of Covid-19 June 2020.

People with weak immune systems were more vulnerable to negative outcomes from the virus and the elderly being more likely to die from COVID-19 may also have had the side effect of reducing the number of old people with a diagnosis of a new case of cancer. This is probably the sort of question that might be able to be tested by those with access to the Scottish Cancer Registry to track patients with other multiple conditions.

What might be worth watching is which cancer sites are in a higher position in the 2021 table as this may show cancers that are starting to become more prevalent. e.g. “Malignant melanoma of the skin” and “Head and neck” have moved to positions ahead of “Rectum and rectosigmoid junction” and “Kidney” now makes the top 10 whereas “Non-Hodgkin lymphoma” drops to 11th.

Incidences by Age Range, Sex and Cancer Site

Here we have age-related data where incidences have been provided in 5-year categories from 0, .. to 90+. This data gives us the chance to consider the relationship between ageing and risk of being diagnosed with a new cancer.

We see 4 main cancers dominating in terms of numbers Colorectal/Lung/Breast and Prostate. The pattern over many cancers in terms of age range is that most of them really become much more prevalent from middle age onwards, peaking for new cases for most sites when we are in our 70s.

Of these big 4 “Breast” seems highest at younger ages than the other 3 so awareness raising should start in younger age groups. The ones that buck that trend higher more in the first half of life tend to be the ones associated with “Cervix uteri” (Cervical) in females and “Testis” (Testicular) in males.

Suggestion:

  • Is the public aware of the increased risk simply by ageing? Are there opportunities to raise awareness among people engaging with other health or public sector organisations to be watchful for early symptoms that might be higher risks according to the age of the person.

  • There are already screening programmes for breast/bowel and cervical cancer. Lung and Prostate cancer are some of the top in terms of numbers. Is there some equivalent of screening for these two in particular? If not, keep informed of any developments in early detection of these two.

Project Output: Cancer Risk Tool

In the course of this analysis an interactive Cancer Risk Tool has been produced that allows users to experiment with changing age/sex and cancer site and getting an idea of what the risk of that combination might be. This is leveraging the value of a multi-decade dataset in capturing risk in Scotland.

Technical Note:

The tool will be found in the “cancer_risk_tool” folder that accompanies this report. It is an experimental demo and requires the user to run the Shiny R Markdown document by opening the file and clicking “Run Document”.
